# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arsinoe-gulf-of-suez
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The ***Aegyptiaca*** (*Koine* Greek: Αἰγυπτιακά, *Aigyptiaka*, "History of Egypt") was a history of ancient Egypt written in Greek by Manetho (fl.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] 290 – 260 BCE), a high priest of the ancient Egyptian religion, in the early 3rd century BCE at the beginning of the Ptolemaic Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] As an Egyptian intellectual who wrote in Greek about his civilization's very long history—over two thousand years old when he wrote his history—Manetho mediated Egyptian and Greek cultures at the dawn of the Hellenistic period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] His *Aegyptiaca* was a comprehensive history of ancient Egypt and stands as a unique achievement in the corpus of ancient Egyptian literature.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] It continues to be a vital subject in Egyptology, and an important resource in the refinement of Egyptian chronology.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho's purpose was to instruct the Greek-speaking world of the Eastern Mediterranean about Egypt's deep past.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] His work provided a clear chronology of Egypt from the first pharaoh of a unified Upper and Lower Egypt, dated by modern historians to 3100 BCE, to just before Alexander's entry into the country following the Siege of Gaza in 332 BCE.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho prefaced his human chronology with the "history" of a mythical era of divine rule that linked Egyptian gods with their Greek counterparts, an equivalence already established by Manetho's time.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The complete text of the *Aegyptiaca* has not survived and is now a lost literary work.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Indirect literary fragments of the text do, however, remain.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho drew upon official records and priestly and oral traditions as sources.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] He integrated ahistorical myth and folkloric elements into recorded history and religious texts that treated the subject of divine kingship.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] His king-lists—some verified by modern scholars, others shown to spurious or inaccurate—provide valuable data that allow Egyptologists to cross-reference names and timelines with written Egyptian records and the archaeological evidence.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The remaining fragments of *Aegyptiaca* constituted an essential—but indirect and at times uncertain—source for understanding Egypt's distant past for over two millennia, long after the use and knowledge of Egyptian hieroglyphic and demotic disappeared in the fifth century CE.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Until the decipherment of ancient Egyptian scripts in the early 19th century CE, the Greek fragments were one of the few resources available to Egyptologists to access the civilization's own recorded history.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Historians, authors, and scholars continue to rely on these fragments even into the modern era.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho's Greek transliteration of Ancient Egyptian divine and pharaonic names challenged later scholars, but ultimately enabled wider popular comprehension.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Indeed, numerous names for Egyptian figures in contemporary Egyptological texts trace their origins to Manetho's Greek renditions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho's organization of the *Aegyptiaca* into thirty-one dynasties of Ancient Egypt (thirty in some sources) remains a defining structural innovation of his work; indeed he is credited with coining the concept of dynastic succession.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Remarkably, his dynastic system continues to serve as the foundation for modern Egyptian chronology.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Although the original *Aegyptiaca* of Manetho is lost, its scope and structure can be reasonably inferred from allusions and epitomes transmitted by later writers as fragments.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The epitomes largely removed Manetho's narrative component and focused solely on succession and reign lengths.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] What narrative fragments have survived demonstrate Manetho's notable command of *Koine* Greek prose and style.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The *Aegyptiaca* was a chronicle likely composed of three papyrus scrolls (Gr: *tomoi*, rendered as "books" or "volumes" in most translations), which together presented an account of Egypt's rulers that spanned over two-and-a-half millennia.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] In the "pre-dynastic" section of Volume One, Manetho integrated mythical accounts of Egyptian gods and heroes, using already-established names and equivalencies of their Greek counterparts.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho used "dynasty" in a manner distinct from its earlier more general association with power or government (see: δυναστεία).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] He considered dynastic changes as not just familial but also geographic, such as moving the capital city or a change in political power centers; in this way his usage differs somewhat from the modern sense.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Complementing his dynastic structure, Manetho provided reign lengths for individual rulers and, at times, total durations for entire dynasties.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] He likely drew upon archives that employed regnal years for dating; the sophisticated Egyptian calendar counted a year as 365 days.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Evidence from the surviving fragments suggests that the *Aegyptiaca* was more than a mere list of names and dates, and likely incorporated short anecdotes, explanations of Ancient Egyptian royal titulary, and summaries of significant events or reigns.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho's organization was strictly by dynasty; the periodization of ancient Egypt is a modern concept, based in part on his dynastic structure.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] His human history covered about 1,110 years in the first volume.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Starting at the unification of Upper and Lower Egypt under the first pharaoh Menes, he then progressed through the rulers of Dynasties I through XI.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho portrayed Dynasties I-VI as a time of unity and innovation, particularly in the emergence of Egyptian hieroglyphics, pyramid-building, and medicine.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] In modern chronology, Dynasties I and II are considered the Early Dynastic and III–VI the Old Kingdom periods.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] While Manetho did not use the modern periodization of ancient Egypt, his outline of these early dynasties did emphasize the unity and antiquity of pharaonic rule from the start.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The *Aegyptiaca* next described a break in the unified succession of rulers, a rupture which he designated Dynasties VII–X and the early part of XI; these "dynasties" were in fact competing factional claimants, and the historicity of his Dynasty VII is disputed among scholars.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Modern historians call this tumultuous era the First Intermediate period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Volume One concluded with the re-establishment of unified rule under the latter part of Dynasty XI, which marks the beginning of the Middle Kingdom of Egypt in modern chronology.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho intended to show Egypt's history as rooted in a unified kingdom ruled by a continuous succession of divinely-sanctioned dynasties.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Volume Two spanned around 800 years of Egypt's history.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The stability established during the latter half of Dynasty XI continued into XII; this is the Middle Kingdom period in modern chronology.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] With Dynasties XIII and XIV, however, came a return to internal strife and with it, a less-clear succession of rulers.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho wrote that Dynasties XV–XVII marked the arrival and rule of foreign rulers that he called the Hyksos; this time is now known as the Second Intermediate Period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho then told of the expulsion of the foreign rulers and the re-establishment of unified Egyptian rule.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The era of imperial expansion and grandeur during Dynasties XVIII and XIX corresponds to the New Kingdom, and brought the second volume of Manetho's history to its close.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Volume Three of Manetho's *Aegyptiaca* covered nearly 860 years.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] It told of Dynasties XX–XXX (or XXXI); this included both Kushite (Ethiopian) (XXV) rulers and a native "Saite Renaissance" (XXVI).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Achaemenid ("Persian") conquest interrupted native rule (XXVII), followed by three more native dynasties as Persian influence waned, then more Persian rulers of XXXI, and finally the Macedonians.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho's placement of the Macedonian Ptolemaic Dynasty at the beginning of a new era provides a fitting conclusion to his framework.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Though its authenticity is debated, Manetho's inclusion of Dynasty XXXI aligns with his aim to document the totality of ruling powers since unification under the first pharaoh Menes some 2,700 years before the *Aegyptiaca* ends; his comprehensive history already included foreign rulers.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] XXXI was the last complete dynasty before what was, for Manetho, the start of Dynasty XXXII: the Ptolemies.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] 290–260 BCE) was a priest—possibly a high priest of Ra in the temple at Heliopolis—who was likely native to Sebennytus (modern Samannud) in the Nile Delta.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] He lived at the dawn of the Hellenistic period (323–30 BCE), during the reign of Ptolemy I Soter (r.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] 303–282 BCE) or his son Ptolemy II Philadelphus (r.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] In writing his *Aegyptiaca*, Manetho sought to present the depth, grandeur, and primacy of his ancient country to its new rulers and to the wider Hellenistic world.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] As a Heliopolitan priest familiar with sacred records, Manetho likely contrasted his own superior sources with those of earlier Greek historians like Herodotus (c.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] 425 BCE) (known even in his own day as "the Father of Lies") with an aim to correct their accounts.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Sebennytus had a strong Greek culture which certainly aided in the bilingual Manetho's familiarity with earlier Greek accounts of his country.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho's decision to write in *Koine* Greek, which was to become the *lingua franca* of the ancient Eastern Mediterranean, was instrumental in allowing the *Aegyptiaca* to reach a broad audience and to become a foundational text for readers interested in Egypt's history.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] *Aegyptiaca* bridged Egyptian historical tradition and the Hellenistic world; its distribution enabled literate Greek-speakers to access Egypt's ancient—and alien— past.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho concluded his chronicle with the establishment of Ptolemaic rule, an event that marked Egypt's entry into the Greco-Roman world.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho's position would have given him unrestricted access to religious and regnal archives.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] These archives housed temple records, monumental inscriptions, and king-lists which detailed the sequence and reign lengths of the pharaohs.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Surviving examples of Manetho's sources include the Abydos, Saqqara, and Turin King Lists.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] While primarily administrative in purpose, these lists were also of religious significance, as they linked historical pharaohs to *ma'at*, or divine order.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The *Aegyptiaca* opened with lists and narratives of the gods and divine kings who were believed to have laid Egypt's cultural foundations.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] To compose this mythical "pre-history", Manetho would have drawn upon sacred funerary texts such as the Pyramid and Coffin Texts.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Priestly traditions such as genealogies, temple rituals, and accumulated lore would also have served as major sources.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho may have also consulted earlier Egyptian historical or semi-historical writings, if such works were available during his time.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] It is plausible that earlier Egyptian historians or scribes compiled now-lost annals or chronicles; these could have provided narrative details for Manetho's accounts of names, events, and reigns.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Furthermore, Manetho's work can be seen in the context of other historical accounts of Egypt written in Greek, such as that of Hecataeus of Abdera (c.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] 360–290 BCE, author of another lost work also entitled *Aegyptiaca*), though Manetho's was arguably more historically focused.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Indeed, Manetho likely aimed to correct Greek historians, particularly Herodotus.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] As a high priest of the Ancient Egyptian religion, Manetho's deep personal knowledge was itself an indispensable source for his history.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] His priestly knowledge encompassed Egyptian culture, religion, and language; it integrated oral traditions with religious mythology and written history to create a comprehensive narrative of the already-ancient Egyptian civilization.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The loss of Manetho's original *Aegyptiaca* makes impossible a direct engagement with his work; the "*Aegyptiaca*" as we know it is a reconstruction assembled from fragments preserved—or corrupted—by later authors.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] This indirect transmission occurred particularly through excerpts used in Hellenistic-era polemics between Egyptians and Jews claiming cultural primacy, and later by early Christian writers attempting to reconcile Biblical chronology with histories from other ancient sources, such as Manetho's.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] This has resulted in significant difficulties in discerning Manetho's original text, a major challenge in Classics.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Their method of transmission was typically the epitome; these were summaries and excerpts of the original work that they then incorporated into their own writings, thus introducing their own interpretations and biases into Manetho's text.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Josephus claims to quote Manetho—and does so liberally—in his polemic *Against Apion*.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] He used Manetho's text selectively, highlighting points that he thought supported canonical Jewish history and dismissing or arguing against those that did not, all in service of establishing a longer and more venerable Jewish past.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Josephus is the earliest known writer to cite pseudo-Manethonian material (i.e., works historically attributed to Manetho but not accepted as such by modern scholars).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] His polemic provides us with what may be some of the most substantial surviving fragments of Manetho, and these fragments were likely constructs themselves—that is, summaries of Manetho's work made by others, and curated by Josephus to meet his own ends.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Scholars treat his quotations as valuable evidence but also approach them with a critical eye, acknowledging the potential for alteration, interpolation, misinterpretation, or selective presentation.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Indeed, scholarly attempts to disentangle genuine fragments from later interpolations have proven inconclusive.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] According to Josephus in *Against Apion*, some of Manetho's anecdotes on Dynasty XV (the Hyksos) focused on the Jews of Egypt.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] In Josephus's telling, Manetho claimed that these Jews were descendants of foreign conquerors who, mixed with a band of Egyptian lepers and famous for their cruelty and misanthropy, were deposed and then banished to the city of Avaris before finally being expelled from the country.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] According to Israeli historian Benzion Netanyahu, Manetho's work was a seminal antisemitic work.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Netanyahu wrote that when the work was composed, Egypt's Jews were enjoying a positive reputation and were assimilated into Hellenistic culture.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho, according to Netanyahu—who takes Josephus at his word—aimed to undermine their reputation as part of a rebellion against Greek power in Egypt, and wrote the *Aegyptiaca* or this section of it with this explicit purpose.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] While Josephus had explicit apologetic aims in bolstering Jewish history against Greek and Egyptian claims of greater antiquity, the Christian writers Africanus, Eusebius, and Syncellus sought to establish the historical grounding and timeline of their faith.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] This led to attempts to synchronize Manetho's version of Egyptian history with the chronology of the Bible, all within the context of competing claims to primacy.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] While some of this material likely reflects Manetho's original text, other parts may represent later additions, errors introduced during transmission, or the interpretations of those who transmitted the fragments.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Modern scholars approach reconstruction by comparing surviving epitomes and weighing the potential influence of the polemical aims of the later authors on their texts.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Scholars also cross-reference this textual evidence with archaeological findings, aligning king names and reign lengths with the inscriptions, tombs, and monuments which offer independent perspectives.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Surviving native Egyptian king-lists provide valuable tools for verifying or correcting the order of rulers, as they are unadulterated by later external historical debates.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Furthermore, linguistic analysis aids in matching Manetho's Greek renderings of names with their original Egyptian forms, potentially stripping away some of the later interpretive layers added by ancient cultural claimants.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Ultimately, our understanding of Manetho's *Aegyptiaca* is as a composite of partial quotations, summaries, and later historians' versions of the original text, frequently altered to fit a particular argument in an ancient contest to "prove" cultural and religious primacy through greater antiquity.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The reliance on this fragmented and altered evidence necessitates caution when attempting to identify Manetho's original history.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] — Böckh, *Manetho und die Hundssternperiode*, 1845, p.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] The *Aegyptiaca's* most significant legacy is its dynastic framework.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] This division of Egyptian rulers into thirty or thirty-one dynasties remains fundamental to Egyptology; it endures despite its initial flaws and the passage of over two millennia.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Since Syncellus used it in the 9th century CE, Manetho's dynastic system has been the standard approach for presenting the history of Pharaonic Egypt, and scholars continue to employ it as an essential organizational tool.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Manetho's decision to write his *Aegyptiaca* in *Koine* Greek rather than in Egyptian—with its hieroglyphic and demotic scripts—was a fortuitous one.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] This choice ensured that his work could be read not just in his own Hellenistic world, but that it would remain accessible long after the ancient Egyptian language and its writing systems had fallen into disuse by the fifth century CE.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] For centuries before the decipherment of ancient Egyptian scripts, the surviving fragments of the *Aegyptiaca* served as the main textual basis for understanding the sequence of Egyptian rulers, forming a critical foundation for early Egyptological scholarship.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Notably, Jean-François Champollion relied on its king-lists as a key to his pioneering translation of those scripts.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] Despite its fragmentary state, the *Aegyptiaca* has allowed scholars from classical and late antiquity through the modern era to encounter Egypt's profoundly ancient history.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/aegyptiaca] As a native educated Egyptian who wrote for a foreign audience, Manetho, through his *Aegyptiaca,* offered a unique perspective—and one that endures to this day—on Egypt's deep past and its new place in a changing world.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Nicknamed the "Bride of the Mediterranean" and "Pearl of the Mediterranean Coast", the city is a popular tourist destination and a major industrial centre.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It is the sixth-largest city in the Arab world, seventh-largest city in the Middle East, and the eleventh-largest city in Africa.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The capital of the Alexandria Governorate, Alexandria is considered an industrial hub and is home to the Alexandria Shipyard.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The city also has a large financial sector, and its ancient port Alexandria is one of the busiest ports in the country.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria is the host city of the annual Alexandria Mediterranean Countries Film Festival, held at the Bibliotheca Alexandrina.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The city is also the home of the Alexandria Opera House, the Alexandria Museum of Fine Arts and the Alexandria National Museum.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The city hosts many sporting events, and is the home of the association football club Al Ittihad.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria extends beyond its administrative municipal city limits as well as its urban agglomeration, with a population of 6,100,000 in 2023 over an area of 1,661 square kilometres (641 sq mi).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was originally established near an ancient Egyptian settlement named Rhacotis, which later became its Egyptian quarter.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The city was made the capital of the Ptolemaic Kingdom and became the foremost commercial, intellectual, and cultural centre for much of the Hellenistic age and late antiquity; at one time, it was the most populous city in the ancient world.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was best known for the Lighthouse of Alexandria (*Pharos*), one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World; its Great Library, the largest in the ancient world; and the Catacombs of Kom El Shoqafa, one of the Seven Wonders of the Middle Ages.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria retained its status as one of the leading cities of the Mediterranean world for almost a millennium, serving as the Egyptian capital until a new capital was founded at Fustat, now part of Cairo.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The city was a major hub of early Christianity and hosted the Patriarchate of Alexandria, one of the leading Christian centers in the Eastern Roman Empire; the modern Coptic Orthodox Church and the Greek Orthodox Church of Alexandria both lay claim to this ancient heritage.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] By the mid-seventh century, the city continued to serve as a trading hub and naval base.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] From the late 18th century, it was a major centre of the international shipping industry and one of the most important trading centers in the world, owing to the easy overland connection between the Mediterranean and Red Seas and the lucrative trade in Egyptian cotton.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria's rebirth began in the early 19th century under Muhammad Ali, considered the founder of modern Egypt, who implemented infrastructure projects and modernisation efforts.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was located on the earlier Egyptian settlement, which was called Rhacotis (Ancient Greek: Ῥακῶτις, romanized: *Rhakôtis*), the Hellenised form of Egyptian *r-ꜥ-qd(y)t* (Bohairic Coptic: ⲣⲁⲕⲟϯ, romanized: *Rakoti*).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Some of the Alexandrian and Greek populaces, e.g., Hypsicles, also referred to the city as *Alexándreia hḗ prós Aígypton* (Ἀλεξάνδρεια ἡ πρός Αἴγυπτον, "Alexandria near Egypt").
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In the course of Roman rule in Egypt, the city's name was Latinised as *Alexandrēa ad Aegyptum*.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In Coptic, the city continued to be referred to by its earlier name (Rakoti), with only a few exceptions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Radiocarbon dating of seashell fragments and lead contamination show human activity at the location during the period of the Old Kingdom (27th–21st centuries BC) and again in the period 1000–800 BC, followed by the absence of activity after that.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] From ancient sources it is known there existed a trading post at this location during the time of Rameses the Great for trade with Crete, but it had long been lost by the time of Alexander's arrival.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] A small Egyptian fishing village named Rhakotis (Egyptian: *rꜥ-qdy.t*, 'That which is built up') existed since the 13th century BC in the vicinity and eventually grew into the Egyptian quarter of the city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Just east of Alexandria (where Abu Qir Bay is now), there were in ancient times marshland and several islands.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] As early as the 7th century BC, there existed important port cities of Canopus and Heracleion.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The latter was recently rediscovered underwater.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was founded by Alexander the Great in April 331 BC as Ἀλεξάνδρεια (*Alexandreia*), as one of his many city foundations.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] After he captured the Egyptian Satrapy from the Persians, Alexander wanted to build a large Greek city on Egypt's coast that would bear his name.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] He chose the site of Alexandria, envisioning the building of a causeway to the nearby island of Pharos that would generate two great natural harbours.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was intended to supersede the older Greek colony of Naucratis as a Hellenistic center in Egypt and to be the link between Greece and the rich Nile valley.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] A few months after the foundation, Alexander left Egypt and never returned to the city during his life.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] After Alexander's departure, his viceroy Cleomenes continued the expansion.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The architect Dinocrates of Rhodes designed the city, using a Hippodamian grid plan.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Following Alexander's death in 323 BC, his general Ptolemy Lagides took possession of Egypt and brought Alexander's body to Egypt with him.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Ptolemy at first ruled from the old Egyptian capital of Memphis.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In 322/321 BC he had Cleomenes executed.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Finally, in 305 BC, Ptolemy declared himself Pharaoh as Ptolemy I Soter ("Savior") and moved his capital to Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Although Cleomenes was mainly in charge of overseeing Alexandria's early development, the *Heptastadion* and the mainland quarters seem to have been primarily Ptolemaic work.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Inheriting the trade of ruined Tyre and becoming the centre of the new commerce between Europe and the Arabian and Indian East, the city grew in less than a generation to be larger than Carthage.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In one century, Alexandria had become the largest city in the world and, for some centuries more, was second only to Rome.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It became Egypt's main Greek city, with Greek people from diverse backgrounds.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Septuagint, a Greek version of the Tanakh, was produced there.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] By the time of Augustus, the city grid encompassed an area of 10 km2 (3.9 sq mi), and the total population during the Roman principate was around 500,000–600,000, which would wax and wane in the course of the next four centuries under Roman rule.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] This event has been called the Alexandrian pogroms.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The violence was quelled after Caligula intervened and had the Roman governor, Flaccus, removed from the city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In 115 AD, large parts of Alexandria were destroyed during the Diaspora revolt, which gave Hadrian and his architect, Decriannus, an opportunity to rebuild it.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In 215 AD, the emperor Caracalla visited the city and, because of some insulting satires that the inhabitants had directed at him, abruptly commanded his troops to put to death all youths capable of bearing arms.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] On 21 July 365 AD, Alexandria was devastated by a tsunami (365 Crete earthquake), an event annually commemorated years later as a "day of horror".
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was an important city in the early history of Christianity, and played a key role in the development of Christian theology.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In 619, Alexandria fell to the Sassanid Persians.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The city was mostly uninjured by the conquest and a new palace called *Tarawus* was erected in the eastern part of the city, later known as Qasr Faris, "fort of the Persians".
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Although the Byzantine emperor Heraclius recovered it in 629, in 641 the Arabs under the general 'Amr ibn al-'As invaded it during the Muslim conquest of Egypt, after a siege that lasted 14 months.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The first Arab governor of Egypt recorded to have visited Alexandria was Utba ibn Abi Sufyan, who strengthened the Arab presence and built a governor's palace in the city in 664–665.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In reference to Alexandria, Ibn Battuta speaks of a number of Muslim saints that resided in the city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] One such saint was Imam Borhan Oddin El Aaraj, who was said to perform miracles.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Another notable figure was Yaqut al-'Arshi, a disciple of Abu Abbas El Mursi.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Ibn Battuta also writes about Abu 'Abdallah al-Murshidi, a saint that lived in the Minyat of Ibn Murshed.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Although al-Murshidi lived in seclusion, Ibn Battuta writes that he was regularly visited by crowds, high state officials, and even by the Sultan of Egypt at the time, al-Nasir Muhammad.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Ibn Battuta also visited the Pharos lighthouse on two occasions: in 1326 he found it to be partly in ruins and in 1349 it had deteriorated to the point that it was no longer possible to enter.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Throughout the late medieval period, Alexandria re-emerged as a major metropolis and the most important commercial port in Egypt and one of the most important in the Mediterranean.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Jewish traveller Benjamin of Tudela even described it as "a trading market for all nations".
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Indeed, Alexandria was the outlet for all goods coming from Arabia, such as incense, and from India and South-East Asia, such as spices (pepper, cloves, cinnamon, etc.), precious stones, pearls and exotic woods like brazilwood.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] But it was also the outlet for goods from Africa, such as ivory and precious woods.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] These goods arrived in Alexandria after passing through Aden on their way to the Red Sea, then headed up the Red Sea to be unloaded in the port of Aydhab.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] From Aydhab, a caravan took the goods to the Nile, probably to the town of Qus.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] From there, the goods sailed to Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] These goods then found their way to the Alexandria market alongside Egyptian products.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] This route was the cheapest and fastest in comparison with the land routes that reached the Mediterranean from Syria or Constantinople.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Latin merchants (Venetians, Genoese, Pisans, Catalans, Provençals, etc.) thus entered this market.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] As early as the 12th century, the major trading cities had funduqs and consuls in Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] A funduq, in this context is an area, often fortified, within the city dedicated to the community of a trading nation under the authority of a consul.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The consul was responsible for adjudicating disputes between merchants of his nation, and also when a subject of the sultan lodged a complaint against a merchant of their nation.The terms of this installation were often set out in treaties between the sultans and the consuls.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] These treaties were part of a policy pursued by the early Mamluk sultans, who encouraged the arrival of merchants from Europe in Alexandria, since this trade not only brought the sultan considerable revenue, but also enabled him to obtain supplies of wood and iron from Europe.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Later, in the 14th century, the Latin trade in Alexandria was also important for the sultans, as it enabled them to obtain supplies of mameluks (slave-soldiers) often sold by Genoese merchants.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] As this trade was very important to the sultans, they were keen to control the city's institutions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Indeed, in Alexandria, in addition to an Emir (governor), the sultan sent a customs inspector who answered directly to the *nazir al-khas* (person in charge of managing the sultan's patrimony).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Customs was not only responsible for collecting customs duties, but also for the security of the port and its warehouses.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria customs also played a role in commercial arbitration and was the preferred circuit for the sale of products brought in by the merchants, which took place at auction.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] These sales were set up to encourage the merchants to sell their products to or through the sultan, rather than selling them freely on the city's markets.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Latin merchants also had jurisdictional privileges : in addition to being judged by their consul if a subject of the sultan lodged a complaint against them, Latin merchants could not be judged by the qadis (civil judges) but had to be judged by the mazalim (the sultan's courts).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria lost much of its importance in international trade after Portuguese navigators discovered a new sea route to India in the late 15th century.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] This reduced the amount of goods that needed to be transported through the Alexandrian port, as well as the Mamluks' political power.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] After the Battle of Ridaniya in 1517, the city was conquered by the Ottoman Turks and remained under Ottoman rule until 1798.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria lost much of its former importance to the Egyptian port city of Rosetta during the 9th to 18th centuries, and it only regained its former prominence with the construction of the Mahmoudiyah Canal in 1820.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria figured prominently in the military operations of Napoleon's expedition to Egypt in 1798.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] French troops stormed the city on 2 July 1798, and it remained in their hands until the arrival of a British expedition in 1801.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The British won a considerable victory over the French at the Battle of Alexandria on 21 March 1801, following which they besieged the city, which fell to them on 2 September 1801.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Muhammad Ali, the Ottoman governor of Egypt, began rebuilding and redevelopment around 1810 and, by 1850, Alexandria had returned to something akin to its former glory.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Egypt turned to Europe in their effort to modernise the country.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Greeks, followed by other Europeans and others, began moving to the city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In the early 20th century, the city became a home for novelists and poets.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In July 1882, the city came under bombardment from British naval forces and was occupied.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In July 1954, the city was a target of an Israeli bombing campaign that later became known as the Lavon Affair.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] On 26 October 1954, Alexandria's Mansheya Square was the site of a failed assassination attempt on Gamal Abdel Nasser.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Europeans began leaving Alexandria following the 1956 Suez Crisis that led to an outburst of Arab nationalism.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The nationalisation of property by Nasser, which reached its highest point in 1961, drove out nearly all the rest.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria is located in the country of Egypt, on the southern coast of the Mediterranean.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It is a densely populated city; its core areas belie its large administrative area.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The city's geology consists of soil sediments, oolitic sand and clay, oolitic limestone (from the Middle Miocene), grey shelly dolomite, marly dolomite, oncolitic limestone and dolomite, and as well as shelly limestone.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Notes: 2020 CAPMAS projection based on 2017 revised census figures, may differ significantly from 2017 census preliminary tabulations.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The 14 kisms were reported simply as *Alexandria city* by CAPMAS in 2006 but given explosive growth definitions, likely informal, may have changed or may be set to change.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Same area with 12 kisms existed in 1996.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria has a borderline hot steppe and hot desert climate (Köppen climate classification: *BSh*/*BWh*).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Like the rest of Egypt's northern coast, the prevailing north wind, blowing across the Mediterranean, gives the city a less severe climate than the desert hinterland.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Rafah and Alexandria are the wettest places in Egypt; the other wettest places are Rosetta, Baltim, Kafr el-Dawwar, and Mersa Matruh.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria experiences violent storms, rain and sometimes sleet and hail during the cooler months; these events, combined with a poor drainage system, have been responsible for occasional flooding in the city in the past though they rarely occur anymore.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] July and August are the hottest and driest months of the year, with an average daily maximum temperature of 30 °C (86 °F).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Port Said, Kosseir, Baltim, Damietta and Alexandria have the least temperature variation in Egypt.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The highest recorded temperature was 45 °C (113 °F) on 30 May 1961, and the coldest recorded temperature was 0 °C (32 °F) on 31 January 1994.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The annual temperature would increase by 2.8 °C (5.0 °F), and the temperature of the warmest and the coldest month by 2.9 °C (5.2 °F) and 3.1 °C (5.6 °F).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] According to Climate Action Tracker, the current warming trajectory appears consistent with 2.7 °C (4.9 °F), which closely matches RCP 4.5.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Due to its location on a Nile river delta, Alexandria is one of the most vulnerable cities to sea level rise in the entire world.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] According to some estimates, hundreds of thousands of people in its low-lying areas may already have to be relocated before 2030.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Additional accounting for the "low-probability, high-damage events" may increase aggregate risks to US$187 billion for the "moderate" RCP4.5, US$206 billion for RCP8.5 and US$397 billion under the high-end ice sheet instability scenario.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In every single estimate, Alexandria alone bears around half of these costs.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Since sea level rise would continue for about 10,000 years under every scenario of climate change, future costs of sea level rise would only increase, especially without adaptation measures.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Recent studies published in Earth's Future by the American Geophysical Union indicate that rising sea levels are causing increases in coastal aquifer levels, reaching building foundations and accelerating their corrosion and potential collapse.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The study predicts that in 2025, more than 7000 buildings in Alexandria will be at risk of collapse due to these groundwater processes.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] "Alexandria") was the old city that was absorbed into Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Brucheum was the Royal or Greek quarter and formed the most magnificent portion of the city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] , Brucheum was enlarged by the addition of an official quarter, making four regions in all.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The city was laid out as a grid of parallel streets, each of which had an attendant subterranean canal.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Jewish quarter was the northeast portion of the city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Two main streets, lined with colonnades and said to have been each about 60 m (200 ft) wide, intersected in the centre of the city, close to the point where the Sema (or Soma) of Alexander (his Mausoleum) rose.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] This point is very near the present mosque of Nebi Daniel; the line of the great East–West "Canopic" street is also present in modern-day Alexandria, having only slightly diverged from the line of the modern Boulevard de Rosette (now Sharae Fouad).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Traces of its pavement and canal have been found near the Rosetta Gate, but remnants of streets and canals were exposed in 1899 by German excavators outside the east fortifications, which lie well within the area of the ancient city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria consisted originally of little more than the island of Pharos, which was joined to the mainland by a 1,260 m-long (4,130 ft) mole and called the *Heptastadion* ("seven stadia"—a *stadium* was a Greek unit of length measuring approximately 180 m or 590 ft).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The end of this abutted on the land at the head of the present Grand Square, where the "Moon Gate" rose.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] All that now lies between that point and the modern "Ras al-Tin" quarter is built on the silt which gradually widened and obliterated this mole.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Ras al-Tin quarter represents all that is left of the island of Pharos, the site of the actual lighthouse having been weathered away by the sea.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] On the east of the mole was the Great Harbour, now an open bay; on the west lay the port of Eunostos, with its inner basin Kibotos, now vastly enlarged to form the modern harbour.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In Strabo's time (latter half of the 1st century BC), the principal buildings were as follows, enumerated as they were to be seen from a ship entering the Great Harbour.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Great Theater, on the modern Hospital Hill near the Ramleh station.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] This was used by Julius Caesar as a fortress, where he withstood a siege from the city mob after he took Egypt after the battle of Pharsalus.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Behind the Emporium rose the Great Caesareum, by which stood the two great obelisks which became known as "Cleopatra's Needles" and were transported to New York City and London.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] This temple became, in time, the Patriarchal Church, though some ancient remains of the temple have been discovered.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The actual Caesareum, the parts not eroded by the waves, lies under the houses lining the new seawall.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Gymnasium and the Palaestra are both inland, near the Boulevard de Rosette in the eastern half of the town; sites unknown.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Mausolea of Alexander (Soma) and the Ptolemies in one ring-fence, near the point of intersection of the two main streets.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Musaeum with its famous Library and theater in the same region; site unknown.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Serapeum of Alexandria, the most famous of all Alexandrian temples.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Strabo tells that this stood in the west of the city; and recent discoveries go far as to place it near "Pompey's Pillar", which was an independent monument erected to commemorate Diocletian's siege of the city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The names of a few other public buildings on the mainland are known, but there is little information as to their actual position.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] None, however, are as famous as the building that stood on the eastern point of Pharos island.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] There, The Great Lighthouse, one of the Seven Wonders of the World, reputed to be 138 m (453 ft) high, was situated.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The first Ptolemy began the project, and the second Ptolemy (Ptolemy II Philadelphus) completed it, at a total cost of 800 talents.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It took 12 years to complete and served as a prototype for all later lighthouses in the world.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The light was produced by a furnace at the top and the tower was built mostly with solid blocks of limestone.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Pharos lighthouse was destroyed by an earthquake in the 14th century, making it the second longest surviving ancient wonder, after the Great Pyramid of Giza.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] A temple of Hephaestus also stood on Pharos at the head of the mole.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In the 1st century, the population of Alexandria contained over 180,000 adult male citizens, according to a census dated from 32 AD, in addition to a large number of freedmen, women, children and slaves.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Estimates of the total population range from 216,000 to 500,000, making it one of the largest cities ever built before the Industrial Revolution and the largest pre-industrial city that was not an imperial capital.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] "Pompey's Pillar, a Roman triumphal column, is one of the best-known ancient monuments still standing in Alexandria today.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It is located on Alexandria's ancient acropolis—a modest hill located adjacent to the city's Arab cemetery—and was originally part of a temple colonnade.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Including its pedestal, it is 30 m (99 ft) high; the shaft is of polished red granite, 2.7 m (8.9 ft) in diameter at the base, tapering to 2.4 m (7.9 ft) at the top.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The shaft is 88 ft (27 m) high and made out of a single piece of granite.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Its volume is 132 m3 (4,662 cu ft) and weight approximately 396 tons.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Pompey's Pillar may have been erected using the same methods that were used to erect the ancient obelisks.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Roger Hopkins and Mark Lehrner conducted several obelisk erecting experiments including a successful attempt to erect a 25-ton obelisk in 1999.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The catacombs were long forgotten by the citizens until they were discovered by accident in 1900.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The most extensive ancient excavation currently being conducted in Alexandria is known as Kom El Deka.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It has revealed the ancient city's well-preserved theater, and the remains of its Roman-era baths.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Alexandria Naval Unknown Soldier Memorial is a prominent historical monument located in the Manshaya district along the corniche.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Built in 1933 to honor Khedive Ismail, and a statue of him was erected at the top of the monument.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It was later transformed into the Monument to the Unknown Soldier in 1965, and the statue of Khedive Ismail was removed.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The monument is distinguished by its location overlooking the Mediterranean Sea, which has witnessed the glories and heroic deeds of the Egyptian Navy throughout history, and serves as a memorial to its martyrs.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The temple was built in the Ptolemy era and dedicated to Osiris, which finished the construction of Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It is located in Abusir, the western suburb of Alexandria in Borg el Arab city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Only the outer wall and the pylons remain from the temple.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] There is evidence to prove that sacred animals were worshiped there.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Archaeologists found an animal necropolis near the temple.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Remains of a Christian church show that the temple was used as a church in later centuries.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Also found in the same area are remains of public baths built by the emperor Justinian, a seawall, quays and a bridge.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Near the beach side of the area, there are the remains of a tower built by Ptolemy II Philadelphus.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The tower was an exact scale replica of the destroyed Alexandrine Pharos Lighthouse.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Citadel of Qaitbay is a defensive fortress located on the Mediterranean sea coast.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It was established in 1477 AD (882 AH) by the mamluk Sultan Al-Ashraf Sayf al-Din Qa'it Bay.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Citadel is located on the eastern side of the northern tip of Pharos Island at the mouth of the Eastern Harbour.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It was erected on the exact site of the famous Lighthouse of Alexandria, which was one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It was built on an area of 17,550 square metres.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Persistent efforts have been made to explore the antiquities of Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Encouragement and help have been given by the local Archaeological Society and by many individuals.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Excavations were performed in the city by Greeks seeking the tomb of Alexander the Great without success.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The past and present directors of the museum have been enabled from time to time to carry out systematic excavations whenever opportunity is offered; D.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Hogarth made tentative researches on behalf of the Egypt Exploration Fund and the Society for the Promotion of Hellenic Studies in 1895; and a German expedition worked for two years (1898–1899).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] But two difficulties face the would-be excavator in Alexandria: lack of space for excavation and the underwater location of some areas of interest.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Since the great and growing modern city stands immediately over the ancient one, it is almost impossible to find any considerable space in which to dig, except at enormous cost.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Cleopatra VII's royal quarters were inundated by earthquakes and tsunami, leading to gradual subsidence in the 4th century AD.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] This underwater section, containing many of the most interesting sections of the Hellenistic city, including the palace quarter, has been explored since 1992 and is still being extensively investigated by the French underwater archaeologist Franck Goddio and his team.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It raised numerous artefacts, among them a noted head of Caesarion.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The remains of a temple to Isis on the sunken island of Antirhodos in the eastern port of Alexandria have been gradually discovered, excavated and identified over a period of 30 years by Goddio's team and published by the Oxford Centre for Maritime Archaeology in 2025.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Some parts of the city's port being opened up to tourists, to some controversy.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The spaces that are most open are the low grounds to northeast and southwest, where it is practically impossible to get below the Roman strata.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The most important results were those achieved by Dr.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Botti, late director of the museum, in the neighbourhood of "Pompey's Pillar", where there is a good deal of open ground.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Here, substructures of a large building or group of buildings have been exposed, which are perhaps part of the Serapeum.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Nearby, immense catacombs and *columbaria* have been opened which may have been appendages of the temple.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] These contain one very remarkable vault with curious painted reliefs, now artificially lit and open to visitors.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The objects found in these researches are in the museum, the most notable being a great basalt bull, probably once an object of cult in the Serapeum.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Other catacombs and tombs have been opened in Kom El Shoqafa (Roman) and Ras El Tin (painted).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The German excavation team found remains of a Ptolemaic colonnade and streets in the north-east of the city, but little else.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Hogarth explored part of an immense brick structure under the mound of Kom El Deka, which may have been part of the Paneum, the Mausolea, or a Roman fortress.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The making of the new foreshore led to the dredging up of remains of the Patriarchal Church; and the foundations of modern buildings are seldom laid without some objects of antiquity being discovered.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The fertilizer industry represents one of Alexandria's most strategically important economic sectors.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Major producers supply both the domestic agricultural market and international customers.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The city's ammonia and nitrogen fertilizer plants have historically relied on natural gas as a feedstock for hydrogen production.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] These facilities have become central to Egypt's ambitions to develop lower-carbon industrial exports while preserving existing industrial infrastructure.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] During the 2020s, Alexandria increasingly became part of Egypt's national strategy to establish itself as a leading producer of green fuels and clean industrial products.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] A major milestone occurred in 2026 when a memorandum of understanding was signed between the Chinese company UEG, Orascom Construction, Abu Qir Fertilizers, and Alexandria Fertilizers Company (AlexFert) during the Egypt Energy Conference.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The agreement outlined plans to integrate green hydrogen into existing fertilizer production facilities in Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Under the proposal, renewable energy capacity of up to 500 megawatts from wind and solar sources would be developed to power water electrolysis systems for green hydrogen production.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Instead of constructing entirely new ammonia complexes, the project would utilize existing fertilizer plants and gradually replace part of the natural-gas-derived hydrogen currently used in production.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] This approach allows the city to leverage its established industrial base while reducing carbon emissions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The project is expected to support the production of approximately 480 tons of green ammonia per day, positioning Alexandria among emerging centers for low-carbon ammonia production in the Mediterranean region.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The initiative reflects broader global demand for low-emission industrial products, particularly in European markets where environmental standards increasingly influence purchasing decisions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] By incorporating green hydrogen into fertilizer manufacturing, Alexandria's producers aim to access premium export markets and strengthen Egypt's competitiveness in the global energy transition.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] One of the most significant recent industrial expansions involves Prometeon, the global tire manufacturer owned by a Chinese industrial group.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The company already operates a heavy-duty tire factory in the Amreya district, with annual production capacity reaching approximately 1.2 million truck and bus tires.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] A large share of this output is exported to international markets, highlighting Alexandria's role as a manufacturing platform for global supply chains.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In 2026, the company announced plans for a major expansion program valued at nearly US$400 million.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The project includes increasing heavy-duty tire production and constructing a new passenger-car tire factory adjacent to the existing facility.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The new plant is planned to occupy approximately 180,000–200,000 square meters and is expected to produce around 1.5 million passenger-car tires annually.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria has a number of higher education institutions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria University is a public university that follows the Egyptian system of higher education.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Many of its faculties are internationally renowned, most notably the Faculty of Medicine and the Faculty of Engineering.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In addition, the Egypt-Japan University of Science and Technology in New Borg El Arab city is a research university set up in collaboration between the Japanese and Egyptian governments in 2010.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Arab Academy for Science, Technology & Maritime Transport is a semi-private educational institution that offers courses for high school, undergraduate level, and postgraduate students.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It is considered the most reputable university in Egypt after the AUC American University in Cairo because of its worldwide recognition from board of engineers at UK & ABET in US.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Université Senghor is a private French university that focuses on the teaching of humanities, politics and international relations, which mainly recruits students from the African continent.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Other institutions of higher education in Alexandria include Alexandria Institute of Technology (AIT) and Pharos University in Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In September 2023, The Greek University of Patras announced that it is opening a branch in Alexandria, in a first-of-its-kind move by a Greek higher education institution.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Greek university of Patras branch will operate two departments, one Greek-speaking and one English-speaking in the subjects of Greek culture, Greek language and Greek philosophy.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria has a long history of foreign educational institutions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The first foreign schools date to the early 19th century, when French missionaries began establishing French charitable schools to educate the Egyptians.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] As a reaction to the establishment of French religious institutions, a secular (laic) mission established Lycée el-Horreya, which initially followed a French system of education, but is currently run by the Egyptian government.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The only school in Alexandria that completely follows the French educational system is Lycée Français d'Alexandrie (École Champollion).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It is usually frequented by the children of French expatriates and diplomats in Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Italian school is the Istituto "Don Bosco".
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] There are also two German schools in Alexandria which are Deutsche Schule der Borromäerinnen (DSB of Saint Charles Borromé) and Neue Deutsche Schule Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Montessori educational system was first introduced in Alexandria in 2009 at Alexandria Montessori.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Around the 1890s, twice the percentage of women in Alexandria knew how to read compared to Cairo.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] As a result, specialist women's publications like *al-Fatāh* by Hind Nawal, the country's first women's journal, appeared.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The city's principal airport is currently Alexandria International Airport, which is located about 25 km (16 mi) away from the city centre, which is now composed of 2 Terminals.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Terminal 1 is the old terminal which was opened in February 2010 whereas Terminal 2 is the Brand New Terminal and was inaugurated in 2025.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] In addition to these, the city include other major roads such as Fouad Street, considered the oldest street in Alexandria, Suez Canal Street, El-Nabi Daniel Street, Port Said Street, Sultan Hussein Street, and the Ring Road.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria also include several highways, such as the Cairo–Alexandria Desert Road, the Cairo–Alexandria Agricultural Road, and the International Coastal Road.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria has four ports; namely the Western Port also known as *Alexandria Port*.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Also the Dekhela Port is located in the west of the Alexandria Port.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The Eastern Port which is mainly used as a yachting harbour, and Abu Qir Port at the northern east of the governorate.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] It is a commercial port for general cargo and phosphates.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria's intracity commuter rail system extends from Misr Station (Alexandria's primary intercity railway station) to Abu Qir, parallel to the tram line.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The commuter line's locomotives operate on diesel, as opposed to the overhead-electric tram.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria plays hosts to two intercity railway stations; Misr Station and Sidi Gaber railway station (in the district of Sidi Gaber in the centre of the eastern expansion in which most Alexandrines reside), both of which also serve the commuter rail line.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Intercity passenger service is operated by Egyptian National Railways.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Alexandria also includes a public bus transport network operated by the Alexandria Passenger Transport Authority, in addition to other private companies.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Muharram Bek station is considered the main bus station that includes all means of transport that connect with neighboring cities and governorates.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] Construction of the Alexandria Metro was due to begin in 2020 at a cost of $1.05 billion.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] An extensive tramway network was built in 1860 and is the oldest in Africa.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p01] The network begins at the El Raml district in the west and ends in the Victoria district in the east.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The Royal Library of Alexandria, in Alexandria, Egypt, was once the largest library in the world.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] It is generally thought to have been founded at the beginning of the 3rd century BC, during the reign of Ptolemy II of Egypt.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] It was likely created after his father had built what would become the first part of the library complex, the temple of the Muses—the Museion, Greek *Μουσείον* (from which the Modern English word *museum* is derived).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] It has been reasonably established that the library, or parts of the collection, were destroyed by fire on a number of occasions (library fires were common and replacement of handwritten manuscripts was very difficult, expensive, and time-consuming).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] To this day, the details of the destruction (or destructions) remain a lively source of controversy.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The Bibliotheca Alexandrina was inaugurated in 2002, near the site of the old Library.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The library hosts annually the Alexandria International Film Festival.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The Alexandria National Museum was inaugurated 31 December 2003.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] It is located in a restored Italian style palace in Tariq El Horreya Street (formerly Rue Fouad), near the centre of the city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] It contains about 1,800 artifacts that narrate the story of Alexandria and Egypt.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Most of these pieces came from other Egyptian museums.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The museum is housed in the old Al-Saad Bassili Pasha Palace, who was one of the wealthiest wood merchants in Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Construction on the site was first undertaken in 1926.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The Graeco-Roman Museum was the city's main archeological museum, focused on artifacts from its Greco-Roman period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] It was opened in 1892 and was closed in 2005 for extensive renovations and expansion.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The museum re-opened to the public in October 2023.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The Alexandria Museum of Fine Arts is a museum for Egyptian and Middle-Eastern fine art situated in the Moharam Bek neighborhood of Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The museum houses a collection of works by Egyptian artist and a selection of works from Baroque, Romanticism, Rococo and Orientalism.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] In addition, noteworthy examples of carving, printing and sculpture from Egyptian and European artists.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Other museums in the city include the Cavafy Museum, the Museum of Fine Arts, and the Royal Jewelry Museum.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Alexandria Opera House hosts performances of classical music, Arabic music, ballet, and opera.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] During the Hellenistic period, poets evolving in the court of Ptolemy II Philadelphus (Philiscus of Corcyra, Lycophron, Alexander Aetolus, Sositheus,...) are currently known as the Alexandrian Pleiad.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Cavafy, a major Greek poet who was born and lived in Alexandria used several themes associated with this city in his work: "Alexandrian Kings", "In Alexandria, 31 B.C.", "Myres: Alexandria 340 A.D", "Kaisarion" and "The God Abandons Antony".
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The most famous mosque in Alexandria is Abu al-Abbas al-Mursi Mosque in Bahary.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Alexandria is the base of the Salafi movements in Egypt.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Al-Nour Party, which is based in the city and overwhelmingly won most of the Salafi votes in the 2011–12 parliamentary election, supports the president Abdel Fattah el-Sisi.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Alexandria was once considered the third-most important city in Christianity, after Rome and Constantinople.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Until 430, the Patriarch of Alexandria was second only to the bishop of Rome.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The Church of Alexandria had jurisdiction over most of the continent of Africa.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] After the Council of Chalcedon in AD 451, the Alexandrian Church split between the Miaphysites and the Melkites.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The Miaphysites went on to constitute what is known today as the Coptic Orthodox Church.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The Melkites went on to constitute what is known today as the Greek Orthodox Church of Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] In the 19th century, Catholic and Protestant missionaries converted some of the adherents of the Orthodox churches to their respective faiths.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Today the Patriarchal seat of the Pope of the Coptic Orthodox Church is Saint Mark Cathedral (though in practice the Patriarch has long resided in Cairo).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The Apostolic Vicariate of Alexandria in Egypt-Heliopolis-Port Said has jurisdiction over all Latin Catholics in Egypt.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Member churches include Saint Catherine Church in Mansheya and Church of the Jesuits in Cleopatra.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The Saint Mark Church in Shatby, founded as part of Collège Saint Marc, is multi-denominational and holds liturgies according to Latin Catholic, Coptic Catholic and Coptic Orthodox rites.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] In antiquity Alexandria was a major centre of the cosmopolitan religious movement called Gnosticism (today mainly remembered as a Christian heresy).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Alexandria's Jewish community declined rapidly following the 1948 Arab–Israeli War, after which negative reactions towards Zionism among Egyptians led to Jewish residents in the city, and elsewhere in Egypt, being perceived as Zionist collaborators.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Most Jewish residents of Egypt moved to the newly settled Israel, France, Brazil and other countries in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The community once numbered 50,000 but is now estimated at below 50.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The most important synagogue in Alexandria is the Eliyahu Hanavi Synagogue.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The main sport that interests Alexandrians is football, as is the case in the rest of Egypt and Africa.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Alexandria Stadium is a multi-purpose stadium in Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] It is currently used mostly for football matches and was used for the 2006 African Cup of Nations.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The stadium is the oldest stadium in Egypt, being built in 1929.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Alexandria was one of three cities that participated in hosting the African Cup of Nations in January 2006, which Egypt won.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Sea sports such as surfing, jet-skiing and water polo are practiced on a lower scale.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The Skateboarding culture in Egypt started in this city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The city is also home to the Alexandria Sporting Club, which is especially known for its basketball team, which traditionally provides the country's national team with key players.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] The city hosted the AfroBasket, the continent's most prestigious basketball tournament, on four occasions (1970, 1975, 1983, 2003).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Alexandria is also known as the yearly starting point of Cross Egypt Challenge and a huge celebration is conducted the night before the rally starts after all the international participants arrive to the city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandria-p02] Cross Egypt Challenge is an international cross-country motorcycle and scooter rally conducted throughout the most difficult tracks and roads of Egypt.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] The **Alexandrian war**, also called the **Alexandrine war**, was a phase of Caesar's civil war in which Julius Caesar involved himself in an Egyptian dynastic struggle.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Caesar attempted to mediate a succession dispute between Cleopatra and Ptolemy XIII and exact repayment of certain Egyptian debts.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Arriving in Alexandria in October 48 BC and seeking initially to apprehend Pompey, his enemy in the civil war, Caesar found that Pompey had been assassinated by Ptolemy XIII's men.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Caesar's financial demands and high-handedness then triggered a conflict which put him under siege in Alexandria's palace quarter.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Only after external intervention from a Roman client state were Caesar's forces relieved.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] In the aftermath of Caesar's victory at the Battle of the Nile and Ptolemy XIII's death, Caesar installed his mistress Cleopatra as Egyptian queen, with her younger brother as co-monarch.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Ptolemaic Egypt had been in a period of dynastic instability and domestic unrest, including native rebellions against the Hellenistic Ptolemies, for decades prior to the installment of Ptolemy XI Alexander II in 81 BC by Sulla.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] This instability and violence was caused by racial, regional, religious, and economic factors.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Internecine conflict between royal claimants, resentment of Roman interference by the Alexandrians, and Roman interventionism, further contributed to the kingdom's decline.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] In 75 BC, Egyptian Cyrenaica was annexed by Rome.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] In later years, Egypt tried to placate powerful Roman generals in the east during the Third Mithridatic War, such as Lucullus and Pompey.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Ptolemy XII Auletes' rule was regularly challenged both by domestic rebellion and by other claimants requesting Roman support for their own claims against him.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Auletes attempted to cultivate good relations with Egyptian priests, tried to recentre religious practice around himself as a unifying force, and seek Roman support for his rule.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] During Caesar's first consulship in 59 BC, he gave an enormous bribe to Caesar and Pompey to receive an official declaration that he was a Roman "friend and ally".
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] His seeking of Roman friendship was possibly in response to abortive Roman attempts to vassalise the rich kingdom in 65 BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] When Egyptian Cyprus was annexed by Rome in 58 BC, Auletes was driven from his throne by an Alexandrian mob.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Cyprus itself was annexed at the initiative of Publius Clodius Pulcher, who appointed Marcus Porcius Cato as *proquaestor pro praetore* to liquidate the island's wealth, likely to fund a Roman grain project; Auletes' younger brother, who was king there, killed himself in preference to submission.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Driven from his throne and replaced by his daughter, Berenice IV, Auletes travelled to Rome, where he pled his case with Pompey's support.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] After apparent threat to his personal safety, he travelled to Ephesus where he sought sanctuary at the temple of Artemis.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] The consul of 57, Publius Cornelius Lentulus Spinther, was supposed to lead an army to restore Ptolemy, but Roman intervention was forestalled by a Sibylline oracle warning against deployment of an army.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Further Roman debates in 56 BC on whether to intervene and, if so, who to send, were bitter and inconclusive.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Many Roman troops, called the Gabiniani, stayed in Egypt to support the Ptolemaic dynasty and occupy the country.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Auletes' return was marked with the murder of his daughter and her supporters.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Gabinius, upon the expiration of his command, was successfully prosecuted for corruption and sent into exile; Gabinius protested that he had marched out of fear of Berenice's husband's fleet turning piratical, which was seemingly disbelieved.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] When Auletes was unable to make payment on his bribes, he appointed a Roman representative to exact the appropriate monies, but the representative was driven from the kingdom by a mob.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] When Marcus Calpurnius Bibulus, as governor of Syria, sent his sons as ambassadors to recall the Gabiniani to defend against a possible Parthian counter-invasion in 50 BC, they were killed.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Upon Auletes' death in 51 BC, he left the kingdom to his son and daughter, Ptolemy XIII and Cleopatra (aged ten and seventeen, respectively).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] The appropriate will was deposited in the Roman state treasury and named the Roman people as guarantors.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] A power struggle promptly began between Ptolemy XIII and Cleopatra, with Cleopatra attempting to find support from the common Egyptian people: she was the first of the Ptolemies to speak Egyptian and spent money freely to support traditional Egyptian religious cults.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Ptolemy XIII's regents, Pothinus and Achillas, led the cause against her.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] After Caesar's successful invasion of Macedonia and victory at Pharsalus in 48 BC, he put Pompey to flight across the Mediterranean.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Pompey and his family fled first to Lesbos and thence to Alexandria in Ptolemaic Egypt; the new child king of Egypt, Ptolemy XIII, had likely been recognised by the Pompeian senate-in-exile and given Pompey as a guardian.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] When he landed at Pelusium, he was assassinated by two Roman officers who were part of Gabinius' garrison.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Caesar arrived and learnt of the death of Pompey, his former son-in-law, three days later on 2 October.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] After arrival to Alexandria, Caesar's forces seemed to have been kept there by unfavourable winds.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] With some time available and huge financial demands, he demanded payment of some 10 million denarii of the bribes promised to him during his consulship in 59 BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] He also announced that he would arbitrate the succession dispute between Ptolemy XIII and Cleopatra.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Pothinus, the eunuch serving as regent for Ptolemy XIII, sent secret orders to Achillas to summon his army of some 20,000 men to Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] They promptly besieged Caesar in the palace compound.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] After a short truce, Achillas launched an all-out attack.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] In repulsing one of these attacks, Caesar's men set a fire which some sources say spread to and destroyed the Library of Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Caesar sent messengers requesting aid, but it would take some time for it to arrive.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] At the start of the siege, the ostensible enemy leaders were present with Caesar in the palace compound.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Cleopatra smuggled herself into the compound to meet with Caesar, aided by a manservant who rowed her across Alexandria's harbour while hidden in a laundry bag.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Cassius Dio claims that the queen intentionally seduced Caesar; regardless, the two quickly became lovers and Caesar then declared that Auletes' will required Ptolemy XIII and Cleopatra to be joint rulers.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] After Pothinus was discovered to be communicating with the besiegers, he was executed.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Arsinoe escaped and joined the Egyptian army, which proclaimed her queen, and then assassinated Achillas to take control of the force.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Amid rumours of a plot to poison Caesar, he took to drink with his officers.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] The first reinforcements were former Pompeians making their way by sea.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Caesar's men then fought a series of small naval battles to maintain control of the harbour and the possibility of resupply thereby.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] While suffering a setback in a defeat in the harbour where his men were routed to the sea before drowning by the hundreds, Caesar's forces maintained some control of the harbour.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] In late January or early February 47 BC, a deputation of Alexandrians asked Caesar to let Ptolemy XIII go.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] He did so in the hopes that Ptolemy XIII would call off the besiegers.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] After renewed assaults on Caesar's positions, a relief army from Syria came overland led by Mithridates of Pergamum and aided by 3,000 Jews contributed by High Priest Hyrcanus II and led by Antipater.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] After the relief army stormed Pelusium, the Ptolemies sent most of their forces to contest the crossing of the Nile delta.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Caesar moved his men by sea to join with the relief army, leading to the Battle of the Nile.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] After Caesar's arrival to Mithridates camp, Caesar and Ptolemy's forces engaged over across a Nile tributary.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] *Bellum Alexandrinum* – usually ascribed to Aulus Hirtius – relates that Caesar's Germanic auxiliary cavalry acquitted themselves well in running down Ptolemy's light infantry as Caesar's heavy infantry crossed the river on a makeshift bridge, causing much of Ptolemy's army to rout.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] After the victory, the narrative reports Caesar came upon Ptolemy's camp and besieged it.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Continuing, Caesar reported attempted to take it by storm but failed, before discovering and exploiting a weak spot in the camp's defences, leading to a successful attack on that spot which forced Ptolemy's garrison to flight.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] In the flight, Ptolemy's ship reportedly capsized and he drowned.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] After the defeat of Ptolemy XIII's forces, Caesar remained in Egypt for some time.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] While *Bellum Alexandrinum* "gives the impression that...
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Caesar left Egypt almost immediately", many modern scholars believe he remained there until June or July, possibly holidaying on the Nile with Cleopatra.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Caesar departed due to news of Pharnaces II's invasion of Roman Asia.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] He left Cleopatra and Ptolemy XIV Philopator (Cleopatra's yet-younger brother) to rule Egypt with the support of three legions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/alexandrian-war] Around June, Cleopatra bore Caesarion, whom Caesar believed to be his child (contra Octavian's later protests).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Three centuries after the decline of Mycenaean Greece during the Bronze Age collapse, Greek urban poleis began to form in the 8th century BC, ushering in the Archaic period and the colonization of the Mediterranean Basin.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] This was followed by the age of Classical Greece, from the Greco-Persian Wars to the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC, and which included the Golden Age of Athens and the Peloponnesian War between Athens and Sparta.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The unification of Greece by Macedon under Philip II and subsequent conquest of the Achaemenid Empire by Alexander the Great spread Hellenistic civilization across the Middle East.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period is considered to have ended in 30 BC, when the last Hellenistic kingdom, Ptolemaic Egypt, was annexed by the Roman Republic.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Classical Greek culture, especially philosophy, had a powerful influence on ancient Rome, which carried a version of it throughout the Mediterranean and much of Europe.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] For this reason, Classical Greece is generally considered the cradle of Western civilization, the seminal culture from which the modern West derives many of its founding archetypes and ideas in politics, philosophy, science, and art.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in the Mediterranean region is commonly considered to have begun in the 8th century BC (around the time of the earliest recorded poetry of Homer) and ended in the 6th century AD.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in Greece was preceded by the Greek Dark Ages (c.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] 800 BC), archaeologically characterised by the protogeometric and geometric styles of designs on pottery.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Following the Dark Ages was the Archaic period, beginning around the 8th century BC, which saw early developments in Greek culture and society leading to the Classical period from the Persian invasion of Greece in 480 BC until the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Classical period is characterized by a "classical" style, i.e. one which was considered exemplary by later observers, most famously in the Parthenon of Athens.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Politically, the Classical period was dominated by Athens and the Delian League during the 5th century, but displaced by Spartan hegemony during the early 4th century BC, before power shifted to Thebes and the Boeotian League and finally to the League of Corinth led by Macedon.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] This period was shaped by the Greco-Persian Wars, the Peloponnesian War, and the Rise of Macedon.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Following the Classical period was the Hellenistic period (323–146 BC), during which Greek culture and power expanded into the Near East from the death of Alexander until the Roman conquest.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Roman Greece is usually counted from the Roman victory over the Corinthians at the Battle of Corinth in 146 BC to the establishment of Byzantium by Constantine as the capital of the Roman Empire in 330 AD.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Finally, Late Antiquity refers to the period of Christianization during the later 4th to early 6th centuries AD, consummated by the closure of the Academy of Athens by Justinian I in 529.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The historical period of ancient Greece is unique in world history as the first period attested directly in comprehensive, narrative historiography, while earlier ancient history or protohistory is known from much more fragmentary documents such as annals, king lists, and pragmatic epigraphy.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Herodotus is widely known as the "father of history": his *Histories* are eponymous of the entire field.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Written between the 450s and 420s BC, Herodotus' work reaches about a century into the past, discussing 6th-century BC historical figures such as Darius I of Persia, Cambyses II and Psamtik III, and alluding to some 8th-century BC persons such as Candaules.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The accuracy of Herodotus' works is debated.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Herodotus was succeeded by authors such as Thucydides, Xenophon, Demosthenes, Plato and Aristotle.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Most were either Athenian or pro-Athenian, which is why far more is known about the history and politics of Athens than of many other cities.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Their scope is further limited by a focus on political, military and diplomatic history, ignoring economic and social history.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The archaic period, lasting approximately from 800 to 500 BC, saw the culmination of political and social developments which had begun in the Greek Dark Age, with the *polis* (city-state) becoming the most important unit of political organisation in Greece.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The absence of powerful states in Greece after the collapse of Mycenaean power, and the geography of Greece, where many settlements were separated from their neighbours by mountainous terrain, encouraged the development of small independent city-states.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Several Greek states saw tyrants rise to power in this period, most famously at Corinth from 657 BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The period also saw the founding of Greek colonies around the Mediterranean, with Euboean settlements at Al-Mina in the east as early as 800 BC, and Ischia in the west by 775.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Increasing contact with non-Greek peoples in this period, especially in the Near East, inspired developments in art and architecture, the adoption of coinage, and the development of the Greek alphabet.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Athens developed its democratic system over the course of the archaic period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Already in the 7th century, the right of all citizen men to attend the assembly appears to have been established.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] After a failed coup led by Cylon of Athens around 636 BC, Draco was appointed to establish a code of laws in 621.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] This failed to reduce the political tension between the poor and the elites, and in 594 Solon was given the authority to enact another set of reforms, which attempted to balance the power of the rich and the poor.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the middle of the 6th century, Pisistratus established himself as a tyrant, and after his death in 527 his son Hippias inherited his position; by the end of the 6th century he had been overthrown, and Cleisthenes carried out further democratising reforms.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In Sparta, a political system with two kings, a council of elders, and five ephors developed over the course of the 8th and 7th centuries.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] According to Spartan tradition, this constitution was established by the legendary lawgiver Lycurgus.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Over the course of the First Messenian War and Second Messenian War, Sparta subjugated the neighbouring region of Messenia, enserfing the population.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the 6th century, Greek city-states began to develop formal relationships with one another, where previously individual rulers had relied on personal relationships with the elites of other cities.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Towards the end of the Archaic period, Sparta began to build a series of alliances, the Peloponnesian League, with cities including Corinth, Elis, and Megara, isolating Messenia and reinforcing Sparta's position against Argos, the other major power in the Peloponnese.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Other alliances in the 6th century included those between Elis and Heraea in the Peloponnese; and between the Greek colony Sybaris in southern Italy, its allies, and the Serdaioi.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In 499 BC, the Ionian city-states under Persian rule rebelled against their Persian-supported tyrant rulers.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Supported by troops sent from Athens and Eretria, they advanced as far as Sardis and burnt the city before being driven back by a Persian counterattack.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The revolt continued until 494, when the rebelling Ionians were defeated.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Darius did not forget that Athens had assisted the Ionian revolt, and in 490 he assembled an armada to retaliate.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Though heavily outnumbered, the Athenians—supported by their Plataean allies—defeated the Persian hordes at the Battle of Marathon, and the Persian fleet turned tail.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Ten years later, a second invasion was launched by Darius' son Xerxes.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The city-states of northern and central Greece submitted to the Persian forces without resistance, but a coalition of 31 Greek city-states, including Athens and Sparta, determined to resist the Persian invaders.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] At the same time, Greek Sicily was invaded by a Carthaginian force.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Persians were decisively defeated at sea by a primarily Athenian naval force at the Battle of Salamis, and on land in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The alliance against Persia continued, initially led by the Spartan Pausanias but from 477 by Athens, and by 460 Persia had been driven out of the Aegean.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] During this long campaign, the Delian League gradually transformed from a defensive alliance of Greek states into an Athenian empire, as Athens' growing naval power intimidated the other league states.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Athens ended its campaigns against Persia in 450, after a disastrous defeat in Egypt in 454, and the death of Cimon in action against the Persians on Cyprus in 450.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] As the Athenian fight against the Persian empire waned, conflict grew between Athens and Sparta.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Suspicious of the increasing Athenian power funded by the Delian League, Sparta offered aid to reluctant members of the League to rebel against Athenian domination.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] These tensions were exacerbated in 462 BC when Athens sent a force to aid Sparta in overcoming a helot revolt, but this aid was rejected by the Spartans.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the 450s, Athens took control of Boeotia, and won victories over Aegina and Corinth.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] However, Athens failed to win a decisive victory, and in 447 lost Boeotia again.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Athens and Sparta signed the Thirty Years' Peace in the winter of 446/445, ending the conflict.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Despite the treaty, Athenian relations with Sparta declined again in the 430s, and in 431 BC the Peloponnesian War began.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The first phase of the war saw a series of fruitless annual invasions of Attica by Sparta, while Athens successfully fought the Corinthian empire in northwest Greece and defended its own empire, despite a plague which killed the leading Athenian statesman Pericles.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The war turned after Athenian victories led by Cleon at Pylos and Sphakteria, and Sparta sued for peace, but the Athenians rejected the proposal.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Athenian failure to regain control of Boeotia at Delium and Brasidas' successes in northern Greece in 424 improved Sparta's position after Sphakteria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] After the deaths of Cleon and Brasidas, the strongest proponents of war on each side, a peace treaty was negotiated in 421 by the Athenian general Nicias.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In 418 BC allied forces of Athens and Argos were defeated by Sparta at Mantinea.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In 415 Athens launched an ambitious naval expedition to dominate Sicily; the expedition ended in disaster at the harbor of Syracuse, with almost the entire army killed, and the ships destroyed.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Soon after the Athenian defeat in Syracuse, Athens' Ionian allies began to rebel against the Delian league, while Persia began to once again involve itself in Greek affairs on the Spartan side.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Initially the Athenian position continued relatively strong, with important victories at Cyzicus in 410 and Arginusae in 406.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] However, in 405 the Spartan Lysander defeated Athens in the Battle of Aegospotami, and began to blockade Athens' harbour; driven by hunger, Athens sued for peace, agreeing to surrender their fleet and join the Spartan-led Peloponnesian League.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Following the Athenian surrender, Sparta installed an oligarchic regime, the Thirty Tyrants, in Athens, one of a number of Spartan-backed oligarchies which rose to power after the Peloponnesian war.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Spartan predominance did not last: after only a year, the Thirty had been overthrown.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The first half of the 4th century saw the major Greek states attempt to dominate the mainland; none were successful, and their resulting weakness led to a power vacuum which was eventually filled by Macedon under Philip II and then Alexander the Great.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the immediate aftermath of the Peloponnesian war, Sparta attempted to extend their own power, leading Argos, Athens, Corinth, and Thebes to join against them.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Aiming to prevent any single Greek state gaining the dominance that would allow it to challenge Persia, the Persian king initially joined the alliance against Sparta, before imposing the Peace of Antalcidas ("King's Peace") which restored Persia's control over the Anatolian Greeks.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] By 371 BC, Thebes was in the ascendancy, defeating Sparta at the Battle of Leuctra, killing the Spartan king Cleombrotus I, and invading Laconia.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Further Theban successes against Sparta in 369 led to Messenia gaining independence; Sparta never recovered from the loss of Messenia's fertile land and the helot workforce it provided.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The rising power of Thebes led Sparta and Athens to join forces; in 362 they were defeated by Thebes at the Battle of Mantinea.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the aftermath of Mantinea, none of the major Greek states were able to dominate.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Though Thebes had won the battle, their general Epaminondas was killed, and they spent the following decades embroiled in wars with their neighbours; Athens, meanwhile, saw its second naval alliance, formed in 377, collapse in the mid-350s.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The power vacuum in Greece after the Battle of Mantinea was filled by Macedon, under Philip II, starting from the battle of Crocus field.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In 338 BC, he defeated a Greek alliance at the Battle of Chaeronea, and subsequently formed the League of Corinth.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Philip planned to lead the League to invade Persia, but was murdered in 336 BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] His son Alexander the Great was left to fulfill his father's ambitions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] After campaigns against Macedon's western and northern enemies, and those Greek states that had broken from the League of Corinth following the death of Philip, Alexander began his campaign against Persia in 334 BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] He conquered Persia, defeating Darius III at the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, and after the Battle of Gaugamela in 331 BC proclaimed himself king of Asia.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] From 329 BC he led expeditions to Bactria and then India; further plans to invade Arabia and North Africa were halted by his death in 323 BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The period from the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC until the death of Cleopatra, the last Macedonian ruler of Egypt, is known as the Hellenistic period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the early part of this period, a new form of kingship developed based on Macedonian and Near Eastern traditions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The first Hellenistic kings were previously Alexander's generals, and took power in the period following his death, though they were not part of existing royal lineages and lacked historic claims to the territories they controlled.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the early part of the Hellenistic period, the exact borders of the Hellenistic kingdoms were not settled.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Antigonus attempted to expand his territory by attacking the other successor kingdoms until they joined against him, and he was killed at the Battle of Ipsus in 301 BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] His son Demetrius spent many years in Seleucid captivity, and his son, Antigonus II, only reclaimed the Macedonian throne around 276.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Meanwhile, the Seleucid kingdom gave up territory in the east to the Indian king Chandragupta Maurya in exchange for war elephants, and later lost large parts of Persia to the Parthian Empire.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] By the mid-3rd century, the kingdoms of Alexander's successors was mostly stable, though there continued to be disputes over border areas.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The great capitals of Hellenistic culture were Alexandria in the Ptolemaic Kingdom and Antioch in the Seleucid Empire.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The conquests of Alexander had numerous consequences for the Greek city-states.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] It greatly widened the horizons of the Greeks and led to a steady emigration of the young and ambitious to the new Greek empires in the east.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Many Greeks migrated to Alexandria, Antioch and the many other new Hellenistic cities founded in Alexander's wake, as far away as present-day Afghanistan and Pakistan, where the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom and the Indo-Greek Kingdom survived until the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Some city-states within Greece formed themselves into two major leagues; the Achaean League (including Corinth and Argos) and the Aetolian League.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] For much of the period until the Roman conquest, these leagues were at war, often participating in the conflicts between the Diadochi's successor states to Alexander's empire.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Antigonid Kingdom became involved in a war with the Roman Republic in the late 3rd century.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Although the First Macedonian War was inconclusive, the Romans, in typical fashion, continued to fight Macedon until it was completely absorbed into the Roman Republic (by 149 BC).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the east, the unwieldy Seleucid Empire gradually disintegrated, although a rump survived until 64 BC, whilst the Ptolemaic Kingdom continued in Egypt until 30 BC when it too was conquered by the Romans.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Aetolian league grew wary of Roman involvement in Greece, and sided with the Seleucids in the Roman–Seleucid War; when the Romans were victorious, the league was effectively absorbed into the Republic.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Although the Achaean league outlasted both the Aetolian league and Macedon, it was also soon defeated and absorbed by the Romans in 146 BC, bringing Greek independence to an end.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Greek peninsula came under Roman rule during the 146 BC conquest of Greece after the Battle of Corinth.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Macedonia became a Roman province while southern Greece came under the surveillance of Macedonia's prefect; however, some Greek *poleis* managed to maintain a partial independence and avoid taxation.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Aegean Islands were added to this territory in 133 BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Athens and other Greek cities revolted in 88 BC, and the peninsula was crushed by the Roman general Sulla.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Roman civil wars devastated the land even further, until Augustus organized the peninsula as the province of Achaea in 27 BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Greece was a key eastern province of the Roman Empire, as the Roman culture had long been in fact Greco-Roman.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Greek language served as a *lingua franca* in the East and in Italy, and many Greek intellectuals such as Galen would perform most of their work in Rome.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The territory of Greece is mountainous, and as a result, ancient Greece consisted of many smaller regions, each with its own dialect, cultural peculiarities, and identity.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Regionalism and regional conflicts were prominent features of ancient Greece.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Cities tended to be located in valleys between mountains, or on coastal plains, and dominated a certain area around them.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the south lay the Peloponnese, consisting of the regions of Laconia (southeast), Messenia (southwest), Elis (west), Achaia (north), Korinthia (northeast), Argolis (east), and Arcadia (center).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] These names survive to the present day as regional units of modern Greece, though with somewhat different boundaries.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Mainland Greece to the north, nowadays known as Central Greece, consisted of Aetolia and Acarnania in the west, Locris, Doris, and Phocis in the center, while in the east lay Boeotia, Attica, and Megaris.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Northeast lay Thessaly, while Epirus lay to the northwest.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Epirus stretched from the Ambracian Gulf in the south to the Ceraunian Mountains and the Aoos river in the north, and consisted of Chaonia (north), Molossia (center), and Thesprotia (south).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the northeast corner was Macedonia, originally consisting Lower Macedonia and its regions, such as Emathia (Macedonia), Pieria, and Bottiaea, and later Almopia, Amphaxitis.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The original capital of Macedon was Aigai and then moved to Pella in the 4th century BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] To the north of Macedonia lay various non-Greek peoples such as the Paeonians due north, the Thracians to the northeast, and the Illyrians, with whom the Macedonians were frequently in conflict, to the northwest.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Chalcidice was settled early on by southern Greek colonists and was considered part of the Greek world, while from the late 2nd millennium BC substantial Greek settlement also occurred on the eastern shores of the Aegean, in Anatolia.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] This was not simply for trade, but also to found settlements.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] These Greek colonies were not, as Roman colonies were, dependent on their mother-city, but were independent city-states in their own right.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Greeks settled outside of Greece in two distinct ways.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The first was in permanent settlements founded by Greeks, which formed as independent poleis.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The second form was in what historians refer to as *emporia*; trading posts which were occupied by both Greeks and non-Greeks and which were primarily concerned with the manufacture and sale of goods.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Examples of this latter type of settlement are found at Al Mina in the east and Pithekoussai in the west.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] From around 750 to 500 BC, Greeks settled colonies in all directions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] To the east, the Aegean coast of Asia Minor was colonized first, followed by Cyprus and the coasts of Thrace, the Sea of Marmara and the south coast of the Black Sea.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Eventually, Greek colonization reached as far northeast as present-day Ukraine and Russia (Taganrog).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] To the west the coasts of Illyria, Southern Italy (called "Magna Graecia") were settled, followed by Southern France, Corsica, and even eastern Spain.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Greek colonies were also founded in Egypt and Libya.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Modern Syracuse, Naples, Marseille and Istanbul had their beginnings as the Greek colonies Syracusae (Συράκουσαι), Neapolis (Νεάπολις), Massalia (Μασσαλία) and Byzantion (Βυζάντιον).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] These colonies played an important role in the spread of Greek influence throughout Europe and also aided in the establishment of long-distance trading networks between the Greek city-states, boosting the economy of ancient Greece.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Ancient Greece consisted of several hundred relatively independent city-states (*poleis*).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] This was a situation unlike that in most other contemporary societies, which were either tribal or kingdoms ruling over relatively large territories.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Undoubtedly, the geography of Greece—divided and sub-divided by hills, mountains, and rivers—contributed to the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] On the one hand, the ancient Greeks had no doubt that they were "one people"; they had the same religion, same basic culture, and same language.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Furthermore, the Greeks were very aware of their tribal origins; Herodotus was able to extensively categorise the city-states by tribe.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Yet, although these higher-level relationships existed, they seem to have rarely had a major role in Greek politics.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The independence of the *poleis* was fiercely defended; unification was something rarely contemplated by the ancient Greeks.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Even when, during the second Persian invasion of Greece, a group of city-states allied themselves to defend Greece, the vast majority of *poleis* remained neutral, and after the Persian defeat, the allies quickly returned to infighting.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Thus, the major peculiarities of the ancient Greek political system were its fragmented nature (and that this does not particularly seem to have tribal origin), and the particular focus on urban centers within otherwise tiny states.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The peculiarities of the Greek system are further evidenced by the colonies that they set up throughout the Mediterranean, which, though they might count a certain Greek *polis* as their 'mother' (and remain sympathetic to her), were completely independent of the founding city.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Inevitably smaller *poleis* might be dominated by larger neighbors, but conquest or direct rule by another city-state appears to have been quite rare.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Instead the *poleis* grouped themselves into leagues, membership of which was in a constant state of flux.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Later in the Classical period, the leagues would become fewer and larger, be dominated by one city (particularly Athens, Sparta and Thebes); and often *poleis* would be compelled to join under threat of war (or as part of a peace treaty).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Even after Philip II of Macedon conquered the heartlands of ancient Greece, he did not attempt to annex the territory or unify it into a new province, but compelled most of the *poleis* to join his own Corinthian League.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Initially many Greek city-states seem to have been petty kingdoms; there was often a city official carrying some residual, ceremonial functions of the king (*basileus*), e.g., the *archon basileus* in Athens.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] However, by the Archaic period and the first historical consciousness, most had already become aristocratic oligarchies.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] It is unclear exactly how this change occurred.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] For instance, in Athens, the kingship had been reduced to a hereditary, lifelong chief magistracy (*archon*) by c.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] 1050 BC; by 753 BC this had become a decennial, elected archonship, and finally an annually elected archonship by 683 BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Through each stage, more power would have been transferred to the aristocracy as a whole, and away from a single individual.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Inevitably, the domination of politics and concomitant aggregation of wealth by small groups of families was apt to cause social unrest in many *poleis*.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In many cities a tyrant (not in the modern sense of repressive autocracies), would at some point seize control and govern according to their own will; often a populist agenda would help sustain them in power.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In a system wracked with class conflict, government by a 'strongman' was often the best solution.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Athens fell under a tyranny in the second half of the 6th century BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] When this tyranny was ended, the Athenians founded the world's first democracy as a radical solution to prevent the aristocracy regaining power.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] A citizens' assembly (the *Ecclesia*), for the discussion of city policy, had existed since the reforms of Draco in 621 BC; all citizens were permitted to attend after the reforms of Solon (early 6th century), but the poorest citizens could not address the assembly or run for office.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] With the establishment of the democracy, the assembly became the *de jure* mechanism of government; all citizens had equal privileges in the assembly.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] However, non-citizens, such as metics (foreigners living in Athens) or slaves, had no political rights at all.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] After the rise of democracy in Athens, other city-states founded democracies.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] However, many retained more traditional forms of government.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] As so often in other matters, Sparta was a notable exception to the rest of Greece, ruled through the whole period by not one, but two hereditary monarchs.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Kings of Sparta belonged to the Agiads and the Eurypontids, descendants respectively of Eurysthenes and Procles.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Both dynasties' founders were believed to be twin sons of Aristodemus, a Heraclid ruler.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] However, the powers of these kings were held in check by both a council of elders (the *Gerousia*) and magistrates specifically appointed to watch over the kings (the *Ephors*).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Only free, land-owning, native-born men could be citizens entitled to the full protection of the law in a city-state.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In most city-states, unlike the situation in Rome, social prominence did not allow special rights.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Sometimes families controlled public religious functions, but this ordinarily did not give any extra power in the government.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In Athens, the population was divided into four social classes based on wealth.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] People could change classes if they made more money.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In Sparta, all male citizens were called *homoioi*, meaning "peers".
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] However, Spartan kings, who served as the city-state's dual military and religious leaders, came from two families.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Women in Ancient Greece appear to have primarily performed domestic tasks, managed households, and borne and reared children.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Slaves had the right to have a family and own property, subject to their master's goodwill and permission, but they had no political rights.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] By 600 BC, chattel slavery had spread in Greece.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] By the 5th century BC, slaves made up one-third of the total population in some city-states.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Between 40 and 80% of the population of Classical Athens were slaves.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Slaves outside of Sparta almost never revolted because they were made up of too many nationalities and were too scattered to organize.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] However, unlike later Western culture, the ancient Greeks did not think in terms of race.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Most families owned slaves as household servants and laborers, and even poor families might have owned a few slaves.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Owners were not allowed to beat or kill their slaves.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Owners often promised to free slaves in the future to encourage slaves to work hard.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Unlike in Rome, freedmen did not become citizens.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Instead, they were mixed into the population of *metics*, which included people from foreign countries or other city-states who were officially allowed to live in the state.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] These public slaves had a larger measure of independence than slaves owned by families, living on their own and performing specialized tasks.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In Athens, public slaves were trained to look out for counterfeit coinage, while temple slaves acted as servants of the temple's deity and Scythian slaves were employed in Athens as a police force corralling citizens to political functions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Sparta had a special type of slaves called *helots*.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Helots were Messenians enslaved en masse during the Messenian Wars by the state and assigned to families where they were forced to stay.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Helots raised food and did household chores so that women could concentrate on raising strong children while men could devote their time to training as hoplites.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Their masters treated them harshly, and helots revolted against their masters several times.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In 370/369 BC, as a result of Epaminondas' liberation of Messenia from Spartan rule, the helot system there came to an end and the helots won their freedom.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] However, it persisted in Laconia until the 2nd century BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] For most of Greek history, education was private, except in Sparta.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] During the Hellenistic period, some city-states established public schools.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Only wealthy families could afford a teacher.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Boys learned how to read, write and quote literature.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] They also learned to sing and play one musical instrument and were trained as athletes for military service.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] They studied not for a job but to become an effective citizen.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Girls also learned to read, write and do simple arithmetic so they could manage the household.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] They almost never received education after childhood.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Boys went to school at the age of seven, or went to the barracks, if they lived in Sparta.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The three types of teachings were: grammatistes for arithmetic, kitharistes for music and dancing, and Paedotribae for sports.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Boys from wealthy families attending the private school lessons were taken care of by a *paidagogos*, a household slave selected for this task who accompanied the boy during the day.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Classes were held in teachers' private houses and included reading, writing, mathematics, singing, and playing the lyre and flute.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] When the boy became 12 years old the schooling started to include sports such as wrestling, running, and throwing discus and javelin.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In Athens, some older youths attended academy for the finer disciplines such as culture, sciences, music, and the arts.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The schooling ended at age 18, followed by military training in the army usually for one or two years.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Some of Athens' greatest such schools included the Lyceum (the so-called Peripatetic school founded by Aristotle of Stageira) and the Platonic Academy (founded by Plato of Athens).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The education system of the wealthy ancient Greeks is also called Paideia.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] At its economic height in the 5th and 4th centuries BC, the free citizenry of Classical Greece represented perhaps the most prosperous society in the ancient world, some economic historians considering Greece one of the most advanced pre-industrial economies.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In terms of wheat, wages reached an estimated 7–12 kg (15–26 lb) daily for an unskilled worker in urban Athens, 2–3 times the 3.75 kg (8.3 lb) of an unskilled rural labourer in Roman Egypt, though Greek farm incomes too were on average lower than those available to urban workers.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] At least in the Archaic period, the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece, with many competing city-states, increased the frequency of conflict but conversely limited the scale of warfare.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Unable to maintain professional armies, the city-states relied on their own citizens to fight.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] This inevitably reduced the potential duration of campaigns, as citizens would need to return to their own professions (especially in the case of, for example, farmers).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Campaigns would therefore often be restricted to summer.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] When battles occurred, they were usually set piece and intended to be decisive.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Casualties were slight compared to later battles, rarely amounting to more than five percent of the losing side, but the slain often included the most prominent citizens and generals who led from the front.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The scale and scope of warfare in ancient Greece changed dramatically as a result of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] To fight the enormous armies of the Achaemenid Empire was effectively beyond the capabilities of a single city-state.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The eventual triumph of the Greeks was achieved by alliances of city-states (the exact composition changing over time), allowing the pooling of resources and division of labor.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Although alliances between city-states occurred before this time, nothing on this scale had been seen before.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The rise of Athens and Sparta as pre-eminent powers during this conflict led directly to the Peloponnesian War, which saw further development of the nature of warfare, strategy and tactics.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Fought between leagues of cities dominated by Athens and Sparta, the increased manpower and financial resources increased the scale and allowed the diversification of warfare.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Set-piece battles during the Peloponnesian war proved indecisive and instead there was increased reliance on attritionary strategies, naval battles and blockades and sieges.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] These changes greatly increased the number of casualties and the disruption of Greek society.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Athens owned one of the largest war fleets in ancient Greece.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] It had over 200 triremes each powered by 170 oarsmen who were seated in 3 rows on each side of the ship.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The city could afford such a large fleet—it had over 34,000 oarsmen—because it owned a lot of silver mines that were worked by slaves.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] According to Josiah Ober, Greek city-states faced approximately a one-in-three chance of destruction during the archaic and classical period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek philosophy focused on the role of reason and inquiry.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In many ways, it had an important influence on modern philosophy, as well as modern science.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Clear unbroken lines of influence lead from ancient Greek and Hellenistic philosophers, to medieval Muslim philosophers and Islamic scientists, to the European Renaissance and Enlightenment, to the secular sciences of the modern day.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Neither reason nor inquiry began with the ancient Greeks.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Defining the difference between the Greek quest for knowledge and the quests of the elder civilizations, such as the ancient Egyptians and Babylonians, has long been a topic of study by theorists of civilization.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The first known philosophers of Greece were the pre-Socratics, who attempted to provide naturalistic, non-mythical descriptions of the world.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] They were followed by Socrates, one of the first philosophers based in Athens during its golden age whose ideas, despite being known by second-hand accounts instead of writings of his own, laid the basis of Western philosophy.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Socrates' disciple Plato, who wrote *The Republic* and established a radical difference between ideas and the concrete world, and Plato's disciple Aristotle, who wrote extensively about nature and ethics, are also immensely influential in Western philosophy to this day.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The later Hellenistic philosophy, also originating in Greece, is defined by names such as Antisthenes (cynicism), Zeno of Citium (stoicism) and Plotinus (Neoplatonism).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek literature was poetry and was composed for performance rather than private consumption.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek poet known is Homer, although he was certainly part of an existing tradition of oral poetry.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Homer's poetry, though it was developed around the same time that the Greeks developed writing, would have been composed orally; the first poet to certainly compose their work in writing was Archilochus, a lyric poet from the mid-7th century BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Tragedy developed around the end of the archaic period, taking elements from across the pre-existing genres of late archaic poetry.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Like poetry, Greek prose had its origins in the archaic period, and the earliest writers of Greek philosophy, history, and medical literature all date to the 6th century BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Prose first emerged as the writing style adopted by the presocratic philosophers Anaximander and Anaximenes—though Thales of Miletus, considered the first Greek philosopher, apparently wrote nothing.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Prose as a genre reached maturity in the classical era, and the major Greek prose genres—philosophy, history, rhetoric, and dialogue—developed in this period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period saw the literary centre of the Greek world move from Athens, where it had been in the classical period, to Alexandria.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] At the same time, other Hellenistic kings such as the Antigonids and the Attalids were patrons of scholarship and literature, turning Pella and Pergamon respectively into cultural centres.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] It was thanks to this cultural patronage by Hellenistic kings, and especially the Museum at Alexandria, that so much ancient Greek literature has survived.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Library of Alexandria, part of the Museum, had the previously unenvisaged aim of collecting together copies of all known authors in Greek.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Almost all of the surviving non-technical Hellenistic literature is poetry, and Hellenistic poetry tended to be highly intellectual, blending different genres and traditions, and avoiding linear narratives.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period also saw a shift in the ways literature was consumed—while in the archaic and classical periods literature had typically been experienced in public performance, in the Hellenistic period it was more commonly read privately.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] At the same time, Hellenistic poets began to write for private, rather than public, consumption.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] With Octavian's victory at Actium in 31 BC, Rome began to become a major centre of Greek literature, as important Greek authors such as Strabo and Dionysius of Halicarnassus came to Rome.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The period of greatest innovation in Greek literature under Rome was the "long second century" from approximately 80 AD to around 230 AD.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] This innovation was especially marked in prose, with the development of the novel and a revival of prominence for display oratory both dating to this period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In Ancient Greek society, music was ever-present and considered a fundamental component of civilisation.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] It was an important part of public religious worship, private ceremonies such as weddings and funerals, and household entertainment.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Men sang and played music at the symposium; both men and women sang at work; and children's games involved song and dance.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek music was primarily vocal, sung either by a solo singer or a chorus, and usually accompanied by an instrument; purely instrumental music was less common.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Greeks used stringed instruments, including lyres, harps, and lutes; and wind instruments, of which the most important was the *aulos*, a reed instrument.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Percussion instruments played a relatively unimportant role supporting stringed and wind instruments, and were used in certain religious cults.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek mathematics contributed many important developments to mathematics, including the basic rules of geometry, the idea of formal mathematical proof, and discoveries in number theory, mathematical analysis, applied mathematics, and approached close to establishing integral calculus.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The discoveries of several Greek mathematicians, including Pythagoras, Euclid, and Archimedes, are still used in mathematical teaching today.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Greeks developed astronomy, which they treated as a branch of mathematics, to a highly sophisticated level.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The first geometrical, three-dimensional models to explain the apparent motion of the planets were developed in the 4th century BC by Eudoxus of Cnidus and Callippus of Cyzicus.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Their younger contemporary Heraclides Ponticus proposed that the Earth rotates around its axis.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the 3rd century BC, Aristarchus of Samos was the first to suggest a heliocentric system.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Archimedes in his treatise The Sand Reckoner revives Aristarchus' hypothesis that *"the fixed stars and the Sun remain unmoved, while the Earth revolves about the Sun on the circumference of a circle"*.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Otherwise, only fragmentary descriptions of Aristarchus' idea survive.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Eratosthenes, using the angles of shadows created at widely separated regions, estimated the circumference of the Earth with great accuracy.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the 2nd century BC Hipparchus of Nicea made a number of contributions, including the first measurement of precession and the compilation of the first star catalog in which he proposed the modern system of apparent magnitudes.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Antikythera mechanism, a device for calculating the movements of planets, dates from about 80 BC and was the first ancestor of the astronomical computer.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] It was discovered in an ancient shipwreck off the Greek island of Antikythera, between Kythera and Crete.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The device became famous for its use of a differential gear, previously believed to have been invented in the 16th century, and the miniaturization and complexity of its parts, comparable to a clock made in the 18th century.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The original mechanism is displayed in the Bronze collection of the National Archaeological Museum of Athens, accompanied by a replica.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The ancient Greeks also made important discoveries in the medical field.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Hippocrates was a physician of the Classical period, and is considered one of the most outstanding figures in the history of medicine.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] He is referred to as the "father of medicine" in recognition of his lasting contributions to the field as the founder of the Hippocratic school of medicine.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] This intellectual school revolutionized medicine in ancient Greece, establishing it as a discipline distinct from other fields that it had traditionally been associated with (notably theurgy and philosophy), thus making medicine a profession.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The art of ancient Greece has exercised an enormous influence on the culture of many countries from ancient times to the present day, particularly in the areas of sculpture and architecture.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the West, the art of the Roman Empire was largely derived from Greek models.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] In the East, Alexander the Great's conquests initiated several centuries of exchange between Greek, Central Asian and Indian cultures, resulting in Greco-Buddhist art, with ramifications as far as Japan.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Following the Renaissance in Europe, the humanist aesthetic and the high technical standards of Greek art inspired generations of European artists.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Well into the 19th century, the classical tradition derived from Greece dominated the art of the Western world.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Religion was a central part of ancient Greek life.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Though the Greeks of different cities and tribes worshipped similar gods, religious practices were not uniform and the gods were thought of differently in different places.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The Greeks were polytheistic, worshipping many gods, but as early as the 6th century BC a pantheon of twelve Olympians began to develop.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Greek religion was influenced by the practices of the Greeks' near eastern neighbours at least as early as the archaic period, and by the Hellenistic period this influence was seen in both directions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The most important religious act in ancient Greece was animal sacrifice, most commonly of sheep and goats.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Sacrifice was accompanied by public prayer, and prayer and hymns were themselves a major part of ancient Greek religious life.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] The civilization of ancient Greece has been immensely influential on language, politics, educational systems, philosophy, science, and the arts.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] It became the *Leitkultur* of the Roman Empire to the point of marginalizing native Italic traditions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] Via the Roman Empire, Greek culture came to be foundational to Western culture in general.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greece] A modern revival of Classical Greek learning took place in the Neoclassicism movement in 18th- and 19th-century Europe and the Americas.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] There are also several historical forms.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ancient-greek-language] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Ankhwennefer's name alludes to *Wn–nfr*, the second name of the divine king Osiris on earth.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Ankhwennefer succeeded Horwennefer as pharaoh in Upper Egypt between 201 and 199; the exact date remains unclear.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] His background is also unknown, but he might have been a relative of Horwennefer, and an inscription at Philae hints at Ankhwennefer being Horwennefer's son.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Historian Joseph Mélèze-Modrzejewski argued that both Ankwennefer and Horwennefer were probably Nubian.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] In contrast, Egyptologist Günther Hölbl argued that demotic sources emphasized that the two rebel leaders were native Egyptians, "reveal[ing] how nationally minded the movement was".
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Either way, both rebel pharaohs stressed their strong connections to Thebes.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] In any case, Ankhwennefer encountered a difficult situation at the start of his reign.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Horwennefer had died and the rebels lost their capital of Thebes either shortly before or after Ankhwennefer's accession.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] The Ptolemaic army garrisoned not just Thebes, but even the town of Syene further to the south.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] According to Egyptologist Toby Wilkinson, Ankhwennefer "daringly" marched his remaining forces into the north, where he plundered and devastated as much as possible to disrupt the Ptolemaic supply lines.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] The rebel pharaoh was probably aided by the outbreak of new anti-Ptolemaic rebellions in the Nile Delta and the Fifth Syrian War between the Ptolemaic Kingdom and the Seleucid Empire.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] In 200 BC, much of the Ptolemaic army was destroyed by the Seleucids in the Battle of Panium; this allowed Ankhwennefer to re-strengthen his regime.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] The rebels' northward offensive succeeded in forcing the Ptolemaic garrison to retreat from Thebes to its southernmost strongholds.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Despite having regained the Thebaid, Ankhwennefer remained beset not just by Ptolemaic loyalists, but also by an invasion by the Kingdom of Kush from the south.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] The latter were exploiting the chaos in Egypt to expand their realm along the Nile, particularly in the area known as Dodekaschoinos.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] In 197 or 196 BC, the Ptolemies launched a counter-offensive and retook Lycopolis in the Delta; this city may or may not have been held by rebels loyal to Ankhwennefer.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Afterwards, Ptolemy V was officially crowned Pharaoh in Memphis.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Deprived of the rich areas in northern Egypt, Ankhwennefer's force was gradually weakened.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] The Kingdom of Kush also continued its pressure from the south.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] The Ptolemaic army advanced southward, retaking Sauty province after heavy fighting, and capturing Thebes in 191.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Ankhwennefer retreated to the border of Kush, and managed to enlist Nubian troops for his cause.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Lloyd argued that these Nubians were possibly interested in protecting the Amun temples at Thebes.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] His last stronghold might have been Syene.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] 186 BC, when Ankhwennefer's Egyptian-Nubian army was decisively defeated.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Ankhwennefer's son was killed in the fighting, but he was captured.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Ankhwennefer was imprisoned, but might have been spared by Ptolemy V after Egyptian priests intervened on his behalf.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Many southern rebels were granted amnesties.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] In the following months, the Ptolemaic army wiped out the remaining rebels in the Delta.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/ankhwennefer-pharaoh] Overall, little is known about the details of his reign as most of the records thereof were destroyed.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/arsinoe-gulf-of-suez] Arsinoe was the capital of the Heroopolite nome, and one of the principal harbors belonging to Egypt.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/arsinoe-gulf-of-suez] It appears to have been also denominated *Cleopatris* (Strabo p.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/arsinoe-gulf-of-suez] It is also conjectured to have stood on the site of the biblical Pi-hahiroth (Pihachiroth).
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/arsinoe-gulf-of-suez] The modern Ardscherúd, a village near Suez, corresponds to this Arsinoe.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/arsinoe-gulf-of-suez] It was seated near the eastern termination of the Royal canal, which communicated with the Pelusiac branch of the Nile, and which Ptolemy Philadelphus carried on from the Bitter Lakes to the head of the Heroopolite gulf.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/arsinoe-gulf-of-suez] The shortness of the road across the eastern desert and its position near the canal were the principal advantages of Arsinoe as a staple of trade.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/arsinoe-gulf-of-suez] But although it possessed a capacious bay, its access from the south was difficult due to the prevailing northern winds.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/arsinoe-gulf-of-suez] Arsinoe, accordingly, was less eligibly situated for the Indian traffic than either Myos Hormos or Berenice.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/arsinoe-gulf-of-suez] Arsinoe is depicted in the first DLC (The Hidden Ones) of the 2017 video game Assassin's Creed Origins.
[src:arsinoe-gulf-of-suez/arsinoe-gulf-of-suez] It is shown as a town occupied by Romans, who tear down ancient Egyptian monuments for use as building materials in 38 BC.
